                                    <div itemprop="article" data-role="panelmod_articleBodyParagraphs">                                                                                                                                                                    <div class="trb_article_page"  data-role="pagination_page" data-content-page="1">                                                                        <p>Like many of the protagonists in his dozens of young adult books, Walter Dean Myers was once a troubled, sensitive and intelligent young man living an aimless life. A writer&#8217;s heart beat in his chest, the passion for words there even as he stumbled through a childhood in the 1940s and '50s scarred by a broken family and an angry Harlem upbringing.</p><p>&#8220;I didn't know I was going to be a writer,&#8221; he said in an <a href="http://www.scholastic.com/teachers/article/walter-dean-myers-interview-transcript">interview </a>with readers of Scholastic Books after his book &#8220;Scorpions&#8221; was published in 1988. &#8220;In fact, I didn't know that there was such a job as an author. No one really encouraged me to write, it was just something I loved to do.&#8221;</p>













 
 









  

  
    
    
    
    
    
    
    
  


